  <main role="main" >
    
    <a id="main-content" tabindex="-1"></a>    

    
          <div class="layout-content">
              <div class="container">
  <div class="row justify-content-center">
    <div class="col-md-10 col-lg-8">

<div class="language-switcher-language-url text-right" id="block-languageswitchercontent" role="navigation">  
    
      
  </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div id="block-particle-content">  
    
      <article>

  
    

  
  <div>
    
<section class="section">


<div class="container">
        
  <div  class="row justify-content-center">
      <div  class="col-md-10 col-lg-8">
      
    
      
<div class="meta-info">
<div class="meta-info-item"><span><time datetime="2020-03-21T07:00:00-04:00" title="Saturday, March 21, 2020 - 07:00">March 21, 2020</time>
</span>
</div>

<div class="meta-info-item">
                  Jamie Rappaport Clark
      </div>
</div>

    
    
      
<div class="fix-images long-text">                  <article class="align-right position-relative embedded-entity">
  
  <div class="embedded-entity-inner">      
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.webp?itok=wdZWtlbS 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.webp?itok=M31HMKP1 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.webp?itok=_u0d3Kw5 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.webp?itok=v9arnU2O 1110w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="623">
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=wdZWtlbS 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=M31HMKP1 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=_u0d3Kw5 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=v9arnU2O 1110w" type="image/jpeg" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="623">
                  <img loading="eager" srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=wdZWtlbS 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=M31HMKP1 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=_u0d3Kw5 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=v9arnU2O 1110w" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="623" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-06/black-wolf_david-friend_3_dsc_black_wolf_9165_2.jpg?itok=wdZWtlbS" alt="Black wolf yellowstone" class="img-fluid">

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">                  David Friend
      </div>
    </div></article>


<p>Twenty-five years ago, we changed the path of Yellowstone National Park for the better. One action changed the soil, the growth of plants and grasses, and the diversity and populations of wildlife throughout the park. It even changed the way the rivers flow. And all we did was bring back wolves.&nbsp;</p>

<p>On January 12, 1995, a motorcade of two park service patrol cars and a truck hauling a horse trailer made their way toward Yellowstone National Park. They stopped at the stone Roosevelt Arch so everyone could take photos under the inscription – “Yellowstone National Park. Created by act of Congress on March 1, 1872. For the benefit and enjoyment of the people.”</p>

<article class="align-center embed-column-extend position-relative embedded-entity">
  
  <div class="embedded-entity-inner">      
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.webp?itok=NNU2q4lr 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.webp?itok=DD0FGTBC 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.webp?itok=L5lUMP1L 737w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="737" height="515">
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=NNU2q4lr 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=DD0FGTBC 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=L5lUMP1L 737w" type="image/jpeg" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="737" height="515">
                  <img loading="eager" srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=NNU2q4lr 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=DD0FGTBC 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=L5lUMP1L 737w" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="737" height="515" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_volunteer_posing_with_landscape_-_dow_0.jpg?itok=NNU2q4lr" alt="Rodger Schlickeisen and volunteer posing with Yellowstone arch and trailer " class="img-fluid">

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">                  Defenders of Wildlife
      </div>
    </div></article>


<p>Inside the trailer were eight gray wolves from Canada. Getting them there was one of our most extraordinary achievements – to right the wrongs that occurred 70 years earlier.&nbsp;</p>

<p>In a little over a decade – from 1914 to 1926 – we <a href="https://www.nps.gov/yell/learn/nature/wolf-restoration.htm" target="_blank">eliminated 136 wolves</a> that lived within the park. This was before we understood the connectedness of wildlife – before we knew the value of intact ecosystems.&nbsp;Before we knew about climate change and biodiversity and loss. Wiping out an apex predator in the park turned out to be a major mistake.</p>

<article class="align-left position-relative embedded-entity">
  
  <div class="embedded-entity-inner">      
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/entry20801.webp?itok=fNw7qjfD 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/entry20801.webp?itok=o9ZLKeS_ 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/entry20801.webp?itok=43JsgBfa 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/entry20801.webp?itok=3uEH9apy 1110w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="499">
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=fNw7qjfD 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=o9ZLKeS_ 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=43JsgBfa 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=3uEH9apy 1110w" type="image/jpeg" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="499">
                  <img loading="eager" srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=fNw7qjfD 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=o9ZLKeS_ 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=43JsgBfa 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=3uEH9apy 1110w" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="499" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/entry20801.jpg?itok=fNw7qjfD" alt="Bull elk crossing stream in Yellowstone NP" class="img-fluid">

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">                  Sandy Sisti
      </div>
    </div></article>


<p>Seventy years without wolves changed Yellowstone – songbirds left, elk and coyotes became overpopulated and beavers disappeared. Elks overgrazed the land and trees, such as willow and aspen. Without those trees, songbirds began to decline. Beavers could no longer build their dams, and streams began to erode and degrade the conditions willow trees needed to grow. Without beaver’s dams and the shade from trees and plants, water temperatures were too high for cold water fish.</p>

<p>In 1973, the Endangered Species Act was passed, and the gray wolf was one of the first species listed as endangered, mandating protection and recovery planning. The long path to recovery in the United States for the wolf had begun. But it was a slow one. It took decades for Americans to come around on wolf reintroduction. &nbsp;</p>

<p>Defenders of Wildlife played a critical role in the reintroduction of gray wolves to the Northern Rockies. Defenders advocated for return of wolves in the midst of proposals, scoping periods, environmental impact statements, public comment periods and draft rulemakings. Many years of advocacy was needed to change people’s misperceptions to ensure the future of the wolf in the U.S.&nbsp;</p>

      </div>
    
    
      
                    <div class="img-mosaic paragraph paragraph--type--image-mosaic paragraph--view-mode--default">
          
                    <div class="img-mosaic-row paragraph paragraph--type--image-mosaic-row paragraph--view-mode--default">
          
<div class="container d-flex mb-2">            <div style="flex: 1.5153583617747;" class="img-mosaic-item">      <article class="position-relative">
  
        
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.webp?itok=3y-0radN 1x" media="(min-width: 992px)" type="image/webp" width="888" height="586"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_991_width/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.webp?itok=qc9PjGMg 1x" media="(min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="888" height="586"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_576_width/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.webp?itok=iILFZ7yi 1x" media="(min-width: 576px)" type="image/webp" width="576" height="380"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.jpg?itok=3y-0radN 1x" media="(min-width: 992px)" type="image/jpeg" width="888" height="586"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_991_width/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.jpg?itok=qc9PjGMg 1x" media="(min-width: 768px)" type="image/jpeg" width="888" height="586"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_576_width/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.jpg?itok=iILFZ7yi 1x" media="(min-width: 576px)" type="image/jpeg" width="576" height="380"/>
                  <img loading="eager" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2020-03/1995_-_yellowstone_wolf_release_-_schlickeisen_and_national_park_service_staff_looking_and_smiling_-_dow.jpg?itok=3y-0radN" width="888" height="586" alt="Rodger Schlickeisen and National Park Service staff at Yellowstone wolf reintroduction" class="img-fluid" />

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">      <div class="visually-hidden">Image Credit</div>
                  Defenders of Wildlife
      </div>
    </article>

    </div>          <div style="flex: 1.3868501529052;" class="img-mosaic-item">      <article class="position-relative">
  
        
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.webp?itok=BxSTsG0a 1x" media="(min-width: 992px)" type="image/webp" width="2000" height="1442"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_991_width/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.webp?itok=BBcJCkK3 1x" media="(min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="991" height="715"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_576_width/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.webp?itok=oCTTVFj5 1x" media="(min-width: 576px)" type="image/webp" width="576" height="415"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.jpg?itok=BxSTsG0a 1x" media="(min-width: 992px)" type="image/jpeg" width="2000" height="1442"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_991_width/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.jpg?itok=BBcJCkK3 1x" media="(min-width: 768px)" type="image/jpeg" width="991" height="715"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/max_576_width/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.jpg?itok=oCTTVFj5 1x" media="(min-width: 576px)" type="image/jpeg" width="576" height="415"/>
                  <img loading="eager" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_size/public/2019-12/rodgeryellowstonerelease.jpg?itok=BxSTsG0a" width="2000" height="1442" alt="Rodger Schlickeisen at Yellowstone release" class="img-fluid" />

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">      <div class="visually-hidden">Image Credit</div>
                  Defenders of Wildlife
      </div>
    </article>

    </div>  </div>
      </div>

      
      </div>

                      <div class="paragraph paragraph--type--text-section paragraph--view-mode--default">
          
<div class="long-text">                  <p>With a lot persistence, it happened. Then-Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt,&nbsp;then-Director of U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Mollie Beattie and then-Superintendent of Yellowstone National Park Mike Finley, set the first wolf crate on the ground in Yellowstone National Park 25 years ago.&nbsp;</p>

<p>The changes in the park have been exciting and significant. Wolf reintroduction caused unanticipated change in Yellowstone. It rebalanced elk and deer populations, allowing the willows and aspen to return to the landscape. The end to overgrazing stabilized riverbanks and rivers recovered and flowed in new directions. Songbirds returned as did beavers, eagles, foxes and badgers. And, <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0153808" target="_blank">while the restoration of wolves in Yellowstone has cost about $30 million total, wolf ecotourism brings in $35 million annually</a>.&nbsp;</p>

<article class="align-center embed-column-extend position-relative embedded-entity">
  
  <div class="embedded-entity-inner">      
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.webp?itok=DZmN7yw4 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.webp?itok=ak-D38OH 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.webp?itok=8a5mh0pS 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.webp?itok=a8F8jW7y 1110w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="620">
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=DZmN7yw4 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=ak-D38OH 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=8a5mh0pS 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=a8F8jW7y 1110w" type="image/jpeg" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="620">
                  <img loading="eager" srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=DZmN7yw4 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=ak-D38OH 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=8a5mh0pS 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=a8F8jW7y 1110w" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="620" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-08/14563692904_e987699582_o.jpg?itok=DZmN7yw4" alt="Morning fog in the Yellowstone River Valley" class="img-fluid">

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">                  Neal Herbert/NPS
      </div>
    </div></article>


<p>This is not only a celebration of wolves and the success of the Endangered Species Act, it is a victory for humans and our planet. The mistake we originally made with the gray wolf was a big one, but our effort to correct that mistake is a beacon of hope.</p>

<p>We face sobering challenges in sustaining life on our planet. The Arctic is at a tipping point, so is the Amazon. We’ve lost <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/3-billion-birds-lost-since-1970-north-america" target="_blank">3 billion birds in North America</a> and <a href="https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/blog/2019/05/nature-decline-unprecedented-report/" target="_blank">1 million species are threatened with extinction within decades</a>. But the gray wolf proves that we can evolve. Over the past 25 years, sustained by the Endangered Species Act and supported by changing public attitudes, wolves have returned to their historical range in the Northern Rockies and the Pacific Northwest, restoring balance to those ecosystems. And the story is not over. We have exciting opportunities to restore gray wolves to Colorado and California, to recover Red Wolves in the Southeast and to rebuild Mexican gray wolf populations in the Southwest.&nbsp;</p>

<article class="align-center embed-column-extend position-relative embedded-entity">
  
  <div class="embedded-entity-inner">      
      <div class="visually-hidden">Image</div>
                      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.webp?itok=cANe3Ptk 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.webp?itok=kbPRxk26 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.webp?itok=Qn7k2j8c 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.webp?itok=ha-3Heae 1110w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="558">
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=cANe3Ptk 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=kbPRxk26 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=Qn7k2j8c 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=ha-3Heae 1110w" type="image/jpeg" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="558">
                  <img loading="eager" srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=cANe3Ptk 510w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_690/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=kbPRxk26 690w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_930/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=Qn7k2j8c 930w, /sites/default/files/styles/original_1110/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=ha-3Heae 1110w" sizes="(min-width:1200px) 1110px, (min-width:992px) 910px, (min-width:768px) 690px, 510px" width="930" height="558" src="/sites/default/files/styles/original_510/public/2019-04/gray_wolf_yellowstone_jacob_w._frank_nps.jpg?itok=cANe3Ptk" alt="Gray Wolf in Yellowstone" class="img-fluid">

  </picture>


      
<div class="image-credit">                  Jacob W. Frank/NPS
      </div>
    </div></article>


<p>Wolves have let us rewrite the history of who we are as people. They are a symbol of the America we want to create – where we can coexist peacefully with wildlife – for their benefit and ours.&nbsp;</p>

      </div>
      </div>

      
  <div class="border-top mt-4 pt-4">  
